As Carolyn wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/25/2004 at 07:47:01 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I am a parent of a 12 year old, who has a keen interest in maths 
>(never my strong point). I know there was a formula for working out 
>combinations and permutations, but it escapes me.  Specifically, 
our 
>problem is:
>
>we have 6 articles of clothing -  2 pairs of pants, two shirts and 
2 
>jumpers each of different colours.  What formula do we use to work 
>out how many outfits can be derived from these 6 articles of 
>clothing, given that you must have 1 of each type of article in the 
>group.  My calculation using a visual calculation presents 8 
>combinations of the clothing or 8 outfits.  Is this correct?


You have 2 choices for each of 3 articles.

  Number of possibilities =  2^3  

                          =  8   (as you found by counting)



